title: For Sale:  Ithaca Coach Gun c.1920
location: Lumberton, NJ  08048, New Jersey, United States
postcontent:
Nothing says "Get off my porch" quite like an Ithaca coach gun. These short double-barreled shotguns are an excellent complement for any home defense strategy. And, with a little practice you can achieve a rate of fire as good or even better than a standard pump action.

This one is close to 100 years old. It was supposedly manufactured some time in the late 19-teens or early 1920s, It is not made of Damascus steel, so modern loads are fine. The fact that I am only asking $200 tells you a lot about its condition. It would probably score out as good condition, but it does have some minor pitting in the bore and the stock was repaired with epoxy resin. I'm going to call it fair condition to avoid arguments. It is certainly suitable for fun at the range.

title: For Sale:  Remington Sportsman 58 SX Sun-Grain Skeet 20 Gauge Shotgun Collector Grade Gold Inlay
location: Sublimity Silverton, East of, Salem, Oregon
postcontent:
Up for sale is a very unique and beautiful, Collector Grade, Remington Sportsman 58 SX with Sun-grain maple stocks.  With factory original “Skeet” barrel.  While most Remington 58s are engraved on both sides of the receiver, this upgraded shotgun also has the original gold inlay.  In addition, this “skeet” model has a different comb than the standard grade and includes the Cutts compensator with original chokes, including the sought after scatter choke.

This firearm has been well cared for, it has no cracks or gouges in the furniture.  Included is the original paperwork from the 1960s and 1970s for small parts/repairs.  This shotgun recently was gone through by a Remington Armor / Gunsmith and it functions flawlessly.  The shotgun is vent-rib barrel and dual bead sight.

It is an excellent clay crushing precision shotgun, with the accessories to get you out hunting.  This shotgun has taken a lot of Doves and Quails.

Here is some background on the 58:
“The model 58, sometimes referred to as the Sportsman 58, was the first gas operated Remington shotgun.  It was introduced in 1956, discontinued in 1963.  It used basically the receiver section of the 870, a modified 870 barrel, and somewhat the marriage of the action slide/forend system of a 11-48 recoil operated gun, converted to make it gas operation.  The Remington 58 was made in 12, 16 and 20ga 2 3/4" chambering plus a separate 12 ga 3" magnum version.  The barrel sported a ventilated rib, with no plain barrels supplied.  This model only holds 2 rounds in the magazine as the recoil spring is inside the forward end of this tube.
The gas system was not self regulating but required the shooter to adjust the regulator to match the loads used.  This regulator also acts as a magazine cap has a Hi and a Low setting.  This is regulated by twisting the end cap to where the marks line up for Hi or Low. This means that if you are using a "trap load", your should use a Low setting, where a heavy duck load is used the Hi setting would be more appropriate.  
Since the complete rear section and receiver were 870 origin, therefore firing pins, extractors, extractor spring and plungers and many of the trigger group parts are the same as for the current model 870.  Operating handles are the same as the model 1100 or the newer 11-87.  Much of the trigger group will be the same as the 1100.  Buttstocks off an 870 will fit as well as the stock bolt and washer.   Forearms will be a problem to find, as any of the newer models do not interchange.  And used 58 forearms come at a premium price.”

It proved excellent for stopping all big game at close range, with the Model 71 being well suited for its delivery. title: For Sale:  Original Russian/Comm Bloc 7.62x54r API Rounds

postcontent:
For sale is 40 Original Russian/ Comm Bloc 7.62x54r API Rounds. For sale by the Round for $4 per Round, $20 per 5 rounds etc. If you want all 40 I will sell them for $150.  These rounds were made in 1966 in Poland which at the time was under the control of the USSR. 

These rounds contain a incendiary element most commonly Phosphorus and Tetryl which detonate upon impact of a hard target such as steel, and hardend concrete. At temperatures in excess of 5000 Degrees, Then after the incendiary activates the Hardend Penetrator passes through the target. Most commonly made of tungsten or depleted uranium.  They will penetrate 3/4 + inches of milde steel and 3/8 inch Ar500 and 1/2 Ar500 after multiple impacts.

These rounds are extremely powerful and need to be fired in a controlled environment because they will start fires. And if you hit a target that will defeat them they can send frag and ricochets.  EXCERCISE EXTREAM CAUTION WHEN FIRING THESE ROUNDS. 

I've placed adds for other lots of this ammo and it always goes quick.
